div.p:
The Seas be our owne, therefore we iourney not ſo farre as the Hollander doth, whereby likewiſe our trauaile and charge muſt be lighter: our ports, harbours and roades be at hand; nay, which is more, all vtenſiles and appurtenances belonging to ſhipping, as is before ſhewed (Pitch and Tarre excepted) are found in our owne Land; whereas they with great coſt, paines, and hazard, fetch them from ſixe ſeuerall places. So then we ſhall be able to affoord better cheape then the Hollanders;
You Engliſh we will make you glad to weare our old ſhooes. and ſo we may ſell when they cannot, and ſo the Engliſh ſhall and may weary them, and weare out thoſe flouts wherewith our poore Fiſher-men are ſcorned. For if they bee put by the vttering of their Herrings abroade, they will bee driuen to leaue their great Ships, and fiſh in ſmaller veſſels neere the

ſhore to ſerue their owne turnes, as heretofore they haue cauſed vs to doe; when as likewiſe on euery tempeſt they openly triumph ouer vs, for not taking the bleſſings of God powred into our lappes.
